d.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold any data on the number and the proportion of care home residents who are malnourished. In 2014 the Government updated the requirements of regulation with the Care Quality Commission (CQC) to provide greater clarity about how the nutritional needs should be met. The CQC can prosecute for a breach of this regulation if a failure to meet the regulation results in avoidable harm to a person using the service, or a person using the service is exposed to significant risk of harm.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","53158 ; 53159","2016-11-18T15:10:45.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637164/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637164/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-15","Malnutrition: Care Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) number and (b) proportion of care home residents who are malnourished; what steps his Department is taking to improve nutrition in care homes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","53160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637165","Department of Health","false","2016-11-18","<p>The 2016-17 budget for the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF) is fixed at £340 million. NHS England has advised that, in order to ensure the Fund does not exceed this budget, a new expenditure control mechanism has been put in place as part of the wider reforms to the Fund which went live on 29 July 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The updated standard operating procedure for the new CDF as set out in <em>‘Appraisal and Funding of Cancer Drugs Fund from July 2016 (including the new Cancer Drugs Fund)’ </em>explained that the following is chargeable against the Fund in 2016-17:</p><p> </p><p>- Drug indications in receipt of interim funding;</p><p>- CDF managed access agreements;</p><p>- Off-label drug indications approved for funding from the Fund;</p><p>- The administrative cost of the CDF (capped at 2% of the fixed £340 million budget in 2016-17);</p><p>- Individual funding requests approved for cancer drugs up to 31 July 2016;</p><p>- Existing CDF drug/indications awaiting reconsideration or appraisal by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE);</p><p>- Drug indications removed from the CDF due to previous reprioritisation exercises or due to NICE/NHS England decisions in so far as they relate to patients who commenced treatment prior to their removal and who remain on treatment; and</p><p>- The cost of the previous CDF for the period from 1 April 2016 to 28 July 2016 when the new arrangements for the Fund were introduced.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has committed to publishing a non-binding forecast for the 2016-17 outturn position in December 2016 and quarterly updates from 2017-18.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-11-18T14:02:49.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637165/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637165/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-15","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much remains in the budget of the Cancer Drugs Fund; and how the monies available to that Fund have been allocated.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","53166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637166","Home Office","false","2016-11-21","<p>We do not hold this information in a format that allows us to provide the information by the provision of the Immigration Rules under which people were present in the UK. To answer this question would require individual analysis of all ETS related case files.</p><p>We continue to release information as part of our Transparency Data and more than 1,400 people were served removal notices in connection with ETS (including those whose leave was revoked) and were detained.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-21T17:50:04.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637166/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637166/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-15","Overseas Students: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many students detained under section 10 of the Immigration and Asylum Act (1999) had their visas revoked as a result of investigations into the Test of English for International Communication operations of Educational Testing Services.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","53164"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637167","Home Office","false","2016-11-21","<p>We do not hold the data in a format that would allow us to provide the information requested. All data relating to Educational Training Services (ETS) is published in the UKVI Transparancy Data, please see link aside:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/temporary-and-permanent-migration-data-august-2016</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-21T18:44:54.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637167/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637167/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-15","Overseas Students: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many students have submitted appeals from (a) inside the UK and (b) outside the UK after revocation of their visas as a result of investigations into the Test of English for International Communication operations of Educational Testing Services.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","53032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637168","Home Office","false","2016-12-13","<p>The total number of working days lost in the Home Office due to mental illness in each of the last three years is set out in the table enclosed.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Working Days Lost as a % of Working Days Available</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01 April 2013 to 31 March 2014</p></td><td><p>0.68%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01 April 2014 to 31 March 2015</p></td><td><p>0.65%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01 April 2015 to 31 March 2016</p></td><td><p>0.79%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Data Source</strong>: Data View - Office for National Statistics complaint monthly</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>snapshot corporated Human Resources data for Home Office</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Period Covered</strong>: Figures are from March 2014, March 2015 and March 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Extraction Date</strong>: 1st April 2014, 2015 and 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Organisational Coverage</strong>: Figures are from the Home Office</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Employee Coverage</strong>: Data is based on all current paid Civil Servants at 31 March 2014,</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>2015 and 2016 and leavers during the previous 12 months</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In the Home Office we are committed to breaking down barriers and reducing stigma for those staff living with mental health conditions. We signed up to the Time to Change pledge in 2014 making a public commitment to be at the forefront of UK employers to tackle mental health issues in the workplace and we remain dedicated to ensuring mental health is a priority. Our specific initiatives are outlined in Annex 1.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-12-13T16:41:59.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637168/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637168/answer","PQ 53071 Annex 1.doc","PQ 53071 Annex 1.doc","Annex 1 - PQ 53071 ","Annex 1 - PQ 53071 ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637168/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-15","Home Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in her Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637169","Home Office","false","2016-11-18","<p>A response to the hon. Member's letter of 23 August 2016 was issued on 16 November 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-11-18T13:30:29.747Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637169/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637169/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-15","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Wolverhampton South West of 23 August 2016, reference ZA3542.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","53023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637170","Home Office","false","2016-11-22","<p>It is intended that the second round of bids for the Places of Worship Security Funding Scheme will open in April 2017. The scheme is funded at £2.4 million over three years with £800,000 being made available for each year of the scheme.</p><p>There is no limit on the amount available for each individual bid but bidders are required to meet 20% of the total cost of the security equipment if successful.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-11-22T12:23:56.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637170/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637170/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-15","Places of Worship Security Funding Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans the second round of bids to open in the Places of worship: security funding scheme; and how much funding she plans to make available (a) in total and (b) for each bid.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","52975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637171","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-21","<p>The additional humanitarian funding announced by the Prime Minister will support:</p><ul><li>those affected by conflict and natural disaster in South Sudan, the Central African Republic, Nigeria, the Sahel, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Burma;</li><li>refugees and displaced people in Uganda, Kenya, Afghanistan, and the Mediterranean region; and</li><li>those affected by El Nino in eastern and southern Africa, including Lesotho, Mozambique and Zimbabwe.</li></ul><p>An additional £80 million will support a new jobs compact in Ethiopia, which will create 100,000 jobs for Ethiopians and refugees. The UK will also contribute £2.5 million to a new fund, led by the International Organisation for Migration, which will facilitate durable solutions for refugees by supporting additional countries to offer resettlement places.</p><p>It is in the UK’s interest to respond quickly to humanitarian crises overseas, offering people protection and opportunities close to their home countries or long-term resettlement in a third country. This saves lives, helps to reduce long-term poverty, and is key to reducing the risk of people being caught up in uncontrolled, mass migration.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-21T15:55:41.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637171/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637171/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what (a) countries and (b) programmes will receive the additional funding announced by the Prime Minister on 21 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","52980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637172","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-22","<p>The number of notified days lost within DFID due to mental illness in each of the last 3 years is detailed in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Sick (Days Lost) to Mental Disorders</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 November 2013 – 31 October 2014</p></td><td><p>1522</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 November 2014 – 31 October 2015</p></td><td><p>1732</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 November 2015 – 31 October 2016</p></td><td><p>1594</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-22T16:56:50.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637172/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637172/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Department for International Development: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in her Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637173","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-21","<p>DFID does not fund any organisations whose projects are administered by the Burmese Army or by military holding companies.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-21T15:57:03.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637173/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637173/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Burma: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of how much of the funding provided by her Department for projects in Burma is administered by companies which are owned by the Burmese Army.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","53018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637174","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-22","<p>DFID discusses issues affecting internally displaced people (IDPs) in Burma with the Burmese authorities on a regular basis. The issue of suicides has not been raised with us as a concern in camps in Burma although we take the welfare of IDPs extremely seriously.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-22T16:56:16.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637174/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637174/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Burma: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her counterpart in Burma on the suicide rates of internally displaced people in camps in that country.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","53017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637175","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-21","<p>The World Health Organisation (WHO) assesses 90-95% of water in Gaza is undrinkable. In the West Bank there is insufficient water to meet the population’s needs. According to WHO, the availability of some medical supplies and services is affected by movement and access restrictions. The UK regularly raises with the Israeli authorities the need to ensure fair access to clean water and medical supplies for the West Bank and Gaza.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-21T15:58:30.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637175/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637175/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Palestinians: Health Services and Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the availability of access to (a) clean water and (b) medical supplies in (i) Gaza and (ii) the West Bank; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","53087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637176","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-11-23","<p>We condemn the continued demolitions of Palestinian property by the Israeli authorities. According to the UN, since the start of 2016, 1010 Palestinian-owned structures were demolished in Area C and in East Jerusalem, displacing 1476 people, including 696 children. Demolitions and evictions of Palestinians from their homes cause unnecessary suffering to ordinary Palestinians; call into question Israel's commitment to a viable two-state solution; and, in all but the most exceptional of cases, are contrary to International Humanitarian Law.</p><p>The UK's position on settlements is clear. They are illegal under international law, present an obstacle to peace, and take us further away from a two-state solution. We strongly urge the Government of Israel to reverse its systematic policy of settlement expansion which distances Israel from its international partners and undermine peace.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-11-23T17:07:55.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637176/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637176/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-15","Occupied Territories: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will estimate the number of Palestinian people displaced from their homes through Israeli settlement building in the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","53085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637177","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-18","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I provided on 17 November to question number 52717.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-18T14:36:31.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637177/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637177/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to increase investment in decentralised renewable energy in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","53140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637178","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-21","<p>No DFID funding for Burma will be administered by the Department for Trade in this financial year and there are no current plans to do so.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-21T17:46:02.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637178/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637178/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Burma: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of her Department's allocated aid for Burma will be administered by the Department for International Trade (a) in this financial year and (b) in the next three financial years.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","53138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637179","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-21","<p>DFID has supported education in DRC since 2013 through scholarships and accelerated learning programmes which focus on primary education and the transition to secondary schooling. We do this through two programmes, Vas-y Fille (‘Go girl’), and Accelere. Vas-y Fille have provided scholarships to over 63,000 girls and enrolled 9,400 out of school girls in accelerated learning programmes. Accelere has enrolled 20,730 new primary school learners, including 10,386 girls. This contributes to the government’s manifesto commitment to provide a decent education to 11 million children.</p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-21T15:48:14.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637179/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637179/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Democratic Republic of Congo: Secondary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support adolescent girls into secondary education in Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC); which programmes her Department supports that address access to secondary education in DRC; and how many girls have been assisted to engage in and to complete secondary schooling as a result of such work in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","53126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637180","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-18","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer I provided on 17 November to question number 52717.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-11-18T14:36:40.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637180/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637180/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","Developing Countries: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to increase provision of decentralised renewable energy in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","53123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637181","Department for International Development","false","2016-11-21","<p>The UK has monitored the situation since the earthquake occurred and stood ready to offer assistance if required.</p><p>The UK will not be providing a response in the aftermath of the earthquake, as the Government of New Zealand have not requested international assistance.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-11-21T17:46:33.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637181/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637181/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-15","New Zealand: Earthquakes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will offer assistance to New Zealand to manage the effects of the recent earthquakes in that country.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","53130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637182","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-23","<p>The learning programmes and the Curriculum in Young Offender Institutions (YOIs) are built on a foundation of literacy and numeracy in line with expectations set out in the National Curriculum.</p><p>In March last year we introduced new education contracts in all public-sector YOIs, which significantly increased the amount of education provision available to young people.</p><p>All children on arrival go through a comprehensive assessment of their education needs, building on any available information from their time in the community. These assessments shape their education programme, if they identify significant literacy issues these will be targeted.</p><p>The Youth Justice Board (YJB) and HM Inspectorate of Prisons (HMIP) publish an annual report on ‘Children in Custody’ that monitors gypsy, traveller and Romany (GRT) children in YOIs and secure training centres (STCs). There is also a direct measure within the education contract which reports on the progress young people make, which is an analysis of the performance and achievement of minority groups against the performance and achievement of wider YOI population. We recognise the importance of improving the literacy of young offenders and will monitor the findings of the latest ‘Children in Custody’ report for 2015-16, including how it relates to GRT children and their ability to understand written English.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-23T13:21:45.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637182/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637182/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-15","Youth Custody: Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 11 November 2016 to Question 51837, what steps her Department plans to take to reduce the difference between Gypsy, Romany or Traveller understanding of written English in young offender institutions and that of other young males.","false","Biography information for Rehman Chishti","Gillingham and Rainham","Rehman Chishti","53135"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637183","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-24","<p>The total working days lost for the past three financial years due to Mental Health related sickness absence is included in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total days lost</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 – 2016</p></td><td><p>167288</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 – 2015</p></td><td><p>171543</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 - 2014</p></td><td><p>152019</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>This data includes staff employed by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ) Headquarters, HM Courts and Tribunals Service, National Offender Management Service, Legal Aid Agency, Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority and Office of the Public Guardian.</p><p> </p><p>The MoJ is committed to supporting the health and wellbeing of all of its employees and to reducing sickness absence levels. The department’s wellbeing strategy, which was launched in November 2015, was designed specifically to reflect the primary causes of sickness absence including mental health. It contains reference to support available to both employees and managers. To coincide with the launch, Directors General in NOMS and MoJ HQ were appointed as senior advocates for attendance management and wellbeing in MoJ.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-24T10:32:06.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637183/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637183/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-15","Ministry of Justice: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in her Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637184","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-18","<p>The Safety in Custody statistics, including data on assaults on prison staff, are published quarterly, and establishment level data is updated annually. The latest bulletin was published on 27 October 2016 and can be found on gov.uk. Assaults on prison officers, which are not recorded separately from those on other members of staff, form the majority of such assaults.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-18T12:54:26.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637184/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637184/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-15","Prisons: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many assaults on prison officers there were in South Yorkshire prisons in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","53036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637185","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-23","<p>We remain vigilant to all incidents involving drones and take the threat they pose to prison security very seriously. A range of methods to counter the threat posed by drones are being trialled and evaluated for their effectiveness across the prison estate. We have already introduced new legislation to further strengthen our powers, making it illegal to land a drone in prison or to use a drone to drop in contraband. We take a zero tolerance approach to smuggling of contraband into prisons and work closely with the police and Crown Prosecution Service to ensure those caught are prosecuted. Anyone found using a drone in an attempt to get contraband into prisons can be punished with a sentence of up to two years imprisonment.</p><p> </p><p>However, I want to do more, specifically by setting up a government taskforce to challenge industry to help in this crucial area with Ministerial colleagues in the Department for Transport, Home Office, Department for Culture, Media and Sport and Ministry of Defence. We will work with drone manufacturers to challenge them to do more to stop the illegal use of drones in prisons.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-11-23T17:42:53.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637185/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637185/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-15","Prisons: Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to her oral contribution of 3 November 2016, Official Report, column 1071, what the (a) remit, (b) membership and (c) date of the last meeting is of the Government taskforce to address the issue of drone use and prisons.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","52984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637186","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-11-18","<p>Information is available on the number of convictions rather than on the number of prosecutions. In the last three years there have been the following number of convictions for breaches of the regulations protecting animal welfare during transport in England and Wales. Separate figures are not kept for convictions relating to live animal exports.</p><p> </p><p>2015 - 8</p><p>2014 - 15</p><p>2013 – 14</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-11-18T09:40:30.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637186/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637186/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-15","Livestock: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many prosecutions there have been for breaches of the animal welfare regulations governing live animal exports in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Williams","Ceredigion","Mr Mark Williams","52955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637187","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Government is committed to making the process of going to court simpler, easier and more sympathetic to victims. That is why we will roll out recorded pre-trial cross-examination in the Crown Court, to ensure vulnerable victims and witnesses are spared the trauma of reliving events at trial.</p><p> </p><p>All publicly-funded advocates in sexual offences cases will be required to undertake specialist training on working with vulnerable victims and witnesses. Only advocates who have had the specialist training will be able to be instructed in and undertake sexual offences cases.</p><p> </p><p>The Law Society and Bar Council are working together to deliver a national training programme, Advocacy and the Vulnerable, which has been developed by the Inns of Court College of Advocacy. Officials engaged with the Inns of Court College of Advocacy during development of the training, and also regularly engage with them to support the development of toolkits for lawyers on the general good practice when dealing with vulnerable witnesses made available on the Advocate’s Gateway which they host.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-11-23T16:34:42.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637187/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637187/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-15","Legal Profession: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions she had with the (a) Law Society and (b) Bar Council before those organisations introduced training for their members on improving the courtroom experience for (i) vulnerable witnesses and (ii) children who have experienced sexual abuse.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","52912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637188","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-11-21","<p>The total working days lost in my Department in each of the last three years due to mental health related sickness absence is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total days lost</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015 – 2016</p></td><td><p>373</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 – 2015</p></td><td><p>325</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013 – 2014</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2016-11-21T14:28:06.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637188/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637188/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-11-15","Northern Ireland Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in his Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637189","Prime Minister","false","2016-11-18","<p>I discussed a range of issues on my visit to India, and launched a senior UK-India strategic dialogue on home affairs issues to make progress on key issues of mutual concern, including opportunities to make the visa system simpler and more efficient, and steps to improve the integrity of border and immigration systems.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2016-11-18T10:19:51.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637189/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637189/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2016-11-15","India: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether during her recent visit to India she discussed the cases of Indian nationals who had their visas curtailed following investigations into the Test of English for International Communication operations of Educational Testing Services; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","53033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637190","Cabinet Office","false","2016-11-18","<p>The House of Lords Appointments Commission (HoLAC) makes recommendations for the appointment of non-party-political members and vets for propriety other nominations to the House of Lords. HoLAC's costs are set out in its annual reports which are available on their website.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","53132","2016-11-18T12:13:19.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637190/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637190/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-15","Peers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the cost of appointing peers to the House of Lords has been for the period between May 2010 and November 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","53169"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637191","Scotland Office","false","2016-11-21","<p>I have regular discussions with my cabinet colleagues, including the Chancellor, on a wide range of issues.</p><p>In February, the Scottish Government and the United Kingdom Government signed the agreement on the Scottish Government’s fiscal framework.</p><p>As set out in the Smith Agreement, changes in the Scottish Government’s block grant will continue to be determined via the operation of the Barnett Formula.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-11-21T14:40:47.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637191/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637191/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-11-15","Public Expenditure: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on future funding for the Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","53121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637192","Scotland Office","false","2016-11-21","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly; all staff that join, do so on an assignment, loan or secondment from other government bodies, mainly the Scottish Government and the Ministry of Justice, who remain the employers. These Departments have their own absence management policies and recording processes that apply to those of their staff working in the office. Detailed reasons for absence attributable to mental illness and other sick absence is not retained by the Scotland Office.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-11-21T14:43:06.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637192/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637192/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-11-15","Scotland Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in his Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637193","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>Stress is the biggest contributor to the category of ‘mental health’ illness. Whilst it affects relatively few members of staff compared to other categories for sickness absence, by its nature a significant number of working days can be lost by those with mental health illness.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport and its agencies have lost the following number of working days due to mental health illness in the last three financial years:</p><p> </p><p>2013/14 – 27908</p><p>2014/15 – 32946</p><p>2015/16 – 28895</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-23T14:52:14.24Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637193/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637193/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Department for Transport: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in his Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637194","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-21","<p>Spending Review 2015 announced an updated long-term funding envelope for delivering the HS2 project of £55.7bn (in 2015 prices), including rolling stock. The project is on time and on budget. HS2 Ltd is committed to managing the cost of HS2 and ensuring maximum value for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport and HS2 Ltd will continue to work with HM Treasury and Infrastructure UK to ensure that the costs of HS2 continue to be kept under control.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-21T14:37:06.91Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637194/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637194/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate he has made of the total cost of the High Speed 2 project; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","53086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637195","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-22","<p>The Department does not hold data which analyses research expenditure in the way requested and the information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-22T13:54:52.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637195/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637195/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Department for Transport: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department has spent on research conducted by (a) private bodies and (b) public bodies in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","53084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637196","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>It is estimated that between 6 April 2015 to 5 April 2016 51.5 full-time equivalent civil servants were employed by the Department for Transport in support of research projects funded by the Department.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-23T14:48:05.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637196/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637196/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Department for Transport: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many full-time equivalent civil servants employed by his Department work in support of research projects funded by his Department; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","53080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637197","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p><strong>a) Highway Maintenance</strong></p><p> </p><p>Just over £9 billion has been invested in highway maintenance since 2011:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>£m</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Local Highways Network Maintenance</p></td><td><p>1006</p></td><td><p>779</p></td><td><p>1073</p></td><td><p>950</p></td><td><p>1156</p></td><td><p>4964</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Highways England Maintenance</p></td><td><p>809</p></td><td><p>708</p></td><td><p>792</p></td><td><p>981</p></td><td><p>955</p></td><td><p>4245</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>1815</p></td><td><p>1487</p></td><td><p>1865</p></td><td><p>1931</p></td><td><p>2111</p></td><td><p>9209</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> (b) Transport infrastructure in each year since 2011</strong></p><p> </p><p>Investing in transport infrastructure to support a strong economy is at the heart of what the Department does. We have invested over £50 billion in the rail network, strategic road network and local transport since 2011:.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>£m</p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Capital DEL</p></td><td><p>7,777</p></td><td><p>7,934</p></td><td><p>8,537</p></td><td><p>9,389</p></td><td><p>5,961</p></td><td><p>39,597</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Capital AME</p></td><td><p>-33</p></td><td><p>-61</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>6,695</p></td><td><p>6,544</p></td><td><p>13,158</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Capital</p></td><td><p>7,744</p></td><td><p>7,873</p></td><td><p>8,549</p></td><td><p>16,084<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>12,505<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>52,755</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><sup>1 </sup>Since Network Rail was reclassified in 2014 the Department for Transport has been funding Network Rail through a loan facility (previously Network Rail had borrowed from the Private Sector). In 2014-15 Network Rail was not consolidated within the Departmental Accounts and therefore the Accounts show that we funded them not only through the Network Grant but also this loan, which were budgeted for in CDEL and CAME respectively. For 2015-16, both of these items scored outside of budgets and instead we fully consolidated Network Rail’s income and expenditure in the Accounts. This is reflected in the change in capital spend figures in 2014/15 and 2015/16.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-23T15:04:00.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637197/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637197/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Transport: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been spent on (a) highway maintenance and (b) transport infrastructure in each year since 2011.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","53103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637198","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>According to estimates made by the Department for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy, the amount of electricity used for road transport in the last 3 years for which data is available is:</p><p> </p><p>2013 33 GWh</p><p>2014 68 GWh</p><p>2015 97 GWh</p><p> </p><p>This is attributed to battery electric and plug-in hybrid vehicles.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-18T11:27:07.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637198/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637198/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Electric Vehicles: Charging Points","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the total electrical output from electrical vehicle chargepoints in the UK in each of the last three years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","53161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637199","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>The Government has implemented measures to encourage cleaner and more fuel efficient HGVs including increasing rewards for renewable gaseous fuels under the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation, the £11m Low Carbon Truck Trial, a £25m Advanced Biofuels Demonstration Competition, and £24 million funding to enable the freight and logistics sector to trial the very latest in innovative low and zero emission vehicle technologies in fleets.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport is making good progress on its review of options to further reduce CO<sub>2</sub> emissions from the road freight sector, which we intend to publish shortly. The Government now looking ahead to our emission reduction plan which will set out the steps we will meet our carbon budgets through the 2020s.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also engaged in EU negotiations on heavy duty vehicle CO<sub>2</sub> regulations, which will cover the monitoring and reporting of fuel consumption and CO<sub>2</sub> emissions from all new HGVs.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-18T11:31:24.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637199/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637199/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Large Goods Vehicles: Greenhouse Gas Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to reduce the level of greenhouse gas emissions from heavy goods vehicles; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","53156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637200","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>In 2015 more ultra low emission vehicles were registered in the UK than in the previous four years combined. The total number of new registrations of ultra low emission vehicles in each year from 2010 to 2015 is published online, and shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>New registrations of ultra low emission vehicles</strong><sup>1</sup><strong> in the UK</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Year of first registration</p></td><td><p>Number of registrations</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>2010<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>1,259</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2,101</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>2012</p></td><td><p>3,346</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>2013</p></td><td><p>4,313</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>2014</p></td><td><p>15,833</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>2015</p></td><td><p>29,972</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>1. 'Ultra low emission vehicles' here includes all vehicles with fully electric powertrains, and cars and vans with tail-pipe emissions below 75 g/km of CO<sub>2</sub> (which will overwhelmingly include plug-in hybrid vehicles).</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>2. Figures for 2010 are for Great Britain registrations only. All other years are United Kingdom. Source: Using vehicle registration data from the table veh0130 at the gov.uk <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/all-vehicles-veh01" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/all-vehicles-veh01</a></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-18T11:06:04.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637200/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637200/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the number of ultra-low emissions vehicles registered in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","53155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637201","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-21","<p>The Government remains absolutely committed to delivering the benefits to passengers of improved services while ensuring we get maximum value for the taxpayer.</p><p>We are making good progress on work to electri‎fy the Great Western main line to Cardiff; and passengers will be able to look forward to improved journeys with more seats when the Intercity Express Programme (IEP) trains come into service.</p><p /><p />","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-21T15:17:04.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637201/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637201/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Railways: Cardiff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to improve rail links with Cardiff.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","53129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637202","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-21","<p>Vehicle noise emissions requirements are harmonized at EU level. Officials from the Department for Transport are actively involved in developing new EU regulations to reduce noise emissions from motorcycles, cars, and commercial vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>More stringent limits for cars and commercial vehicles came into force in July 2016 with further reductions scheduled for 2020 and 2024. The EU Commission are currently studying motorcycle noise. They are obliged to introduce new, more stringent requirements for motorcycles registered after 1 January 2021. The limit values are not yet set, but will be developed together with the United Nations Economic Commission for Europe, in order to obtain wider harmonisation. This work may involve development of a new test procedure.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-21T15:21:11.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637202/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637202/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Motor Vehicles: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce noise emissions from (a) motorcycles, (b) cars and (c) commercial vehicles; and what targets he has set to reduce each such type of noise emission.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","52910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637203","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>The Road Investment Strategy has a £300m Environmental Fund for tackling 1150 Noise Important Areas by 2020. Highways England has undertaken previous research which led to the use of low noise surfacing that is currently used across the strategic road network. Research is ongoing to evaluate the effectiveness of other noise-reducing surfaces deployed across Europe, as well as investigating potential noise mitigation measures for concrete roads.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-18T10:46:12.893Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637203/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637203/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Roads: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what research his Department has conducted on the effectiveness of noise-reducing road surfaces.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","52911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637204","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>The £30m Low Emission Bus Scheme (LEBS) was the first time operators and local authorities in Wales were eligible to apply for funding for low emission buses. We were overbid by four times the amount of funding available, and we were unable to fund the majority of the bids received due to the strong competition. The scheme received four Welsh bids, one of which was successful. Unfortunately, due to reasons entirely separate from the fund, the bidder had to withdraw their application.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-11-23T15:22:48.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637204/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637204/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Buses: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many applications from bus companies based in Wales were submitted for the low emission bus scheme; and how many of those applications were successful.","false","Biography information for Craig Williams","Cardiff North","Craig Williams","52919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637206","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>GTR’s performance is assessed across the whole franchise. If found in breach or default, it would be at the Secretary of State’s discretion to make a decision on next steps, according to provisions in the franchise agreement.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-18T14:14:32.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637206/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637206/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) franchise agreement that stipulates as to whether it is in default of its franchise agreement for cancellations relates to (a) GTR as a whole, (b) Thameslink, Southern, Gatwick Express and Great Northern individually or (c) is at the discretion of the Secretary of State.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","52890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637207","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>GTR’s benchmarks are based on the entire franchise, not each component business group – we do not have that information to that level of disaggregation.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-18T14:00:18.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637207/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637207/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the actual level of cancellations was compared to the default threshold cancellation level for the southern section of the Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) franchise, as amended by the GTR remedial plan, for each monthly period since the beginning of 2016.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","52891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637208","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>GTR’s benchmarks are based on the entire franchise, not each component business group – we do not have that information to that level of disaggregation.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-18T14:04:19.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637208/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637208/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the actual number of train cancellations was compared to the default threshold number of train cancellations for the southern section of the Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) franchise as amended by the GTR remedial plan for each monthly period since the beginning of 2016.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","52892"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637209","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>The performance benchmarks are calculated as a percentage on a moving annual average basis. This is to ensure that an operator’s performance is measured over the long term and not impacted by short term issues. Therefore a comparison of the number of cancellations for each period against a percentage-based annual benchmark is misleading.</p><p> </p><p>We have attached the latest position against the Remedial Plan benchmarks in the table below. Cancellations are in excess of default levels. GTR has submitted a force majeure claim for official and unofficial industrial action undertaken by drivers and conductors on Southern services. The outcome of our assessment of their force majeure claim will determine GTR's performance level.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Railway period</p></td><td><p>Period dates</p></td><td><p>Actual (%)</p></td><td><p>Default (%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16_P10</p></td><td><p>13 Dec to 09 Jan 2016</p></td><td><p>1.80</p></td><td><p>2.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16_P11</p></td><td><p>10 Jan to 06 Feb 2016</p></td><td><p>1.84</p></td><td><p>2.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16_P12</p></td><td><p>07 Feb to 05 Mar 2016</p></td><td><p>1.91</p></td><td><p>2.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16_P13</p></td><td><p>06 Mar to 31 Mar 2016</p></td><td><p>1.95</p></td><td><p>2.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P01</p></td><td><p>01 Apr to 30 Apr 2016</p></td><td><p>1.98</p></td><td><p>2.73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P02</p></td><td><p>01 May to 28 May 2016</p></td><td><p>2.21</p></td><td><p>2.73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P03</p></td><td><p>29 May to 25 Jun 2016</p></td><td><p>2.84</p></td><td><p>2.73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P04</p></td><td><p>26 Jun to 23 Jul 2016</p></td><td><p>3.44</p></td><td><p>2.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P05</p></td><td><p>24 Jul to 20 Aug 2016</p></td><td><p>4.15</p></td><td><p>2.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P06</p></td><td><p>21 Aug to 17 Sep 2016</p></td><td><p>4.75</p></td><td><p>2.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P07</p></td><td><p>18 Sep to 15 Oct 2016</p></td><td><p>5.19</p></td><td><p>2.69</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-18T14:11:52.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637209/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637209/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the actual percentage level of cancellations was compared to the default percentage threshold cancellation level for the Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) franchise, as amended by the GTR remedial plan, for each monthly period since the beginning of 2016.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","52894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637210","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>The performance benchmarks are calculated as a percentage on a moving annual average basis. This is to ensure that an operator’s performance is measured over the long term and not impacted by short term issues. Therefore a comparison of the number of cancellations for each period against a percentage-based annual benchmark is misleading.</p><p> </p><p>We have attached the latest position against the Remedial Plan benchmarks in the table below. Cancellations are in excess of default levels. GTR has submitted a force majeure claim for official and unofficial industrial action undertaken by drivers and conductors on Southern services. The outcome of our assessment of their force majeure claim will determine GTR's performance level.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Railway period</p></td><td><p>Period dates</p></td><td><p>Actual (%)</p></td><td><p>Default (%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16_P10</p></td><td><p>13 Dec to 09 Jan 2016</p></td><td><p>1.80</p></td><td><p>2.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16_P11</p></td><td><p>10 Jan to 06 Feb 2016</p></td><td><p>1.84</p></td><td><p>2.70</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16_P12</p></td><td><p>07 Feb to 05 Mar 2016</p></td><td><p>1.91</p></td><td><p>2.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16_P13</p></td><td><p>06 Mar to 31 Mar 2016</p></td><td><p>1.95</p></td><td><p>2.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P01</p></td><td><p>01 Apr to 30 Apr 2016</p></td><td><p>1.98</p></td><td><p>2.73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P02</p></td><td><p>01 May to 28 May 2016</p></td><td><p>2.21</p></td><td><p>2.73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P03</p></td><td><p>29 May to 25 Jun 2016</p></td><td><p>2.84</p></td><td><p>2.73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P04</p></td><td><p>26 Jun to 23 Jul 2016</p></td><td><p>3.44</p></td><td><p>2.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P05</p></td><td><p>24 Jul to 20 Aug 2016</p></td><td><p>4.15</p></td><td><p>2.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P06</p></td><td><p>21 Aug to 17 Sep 2016</p></td><td><p>4.75</p></td><td><p>2.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17_P07</p></td><td><p>18 Sep to 15 Oct 2016</p></td><td><p>5.19</p></td><td><p>2.69</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-11-18T14:07:43.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637210/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637210/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the actual number of train cancellations was compared to the default threshold number of train cancellations for the Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) franchise, as amended by the GTR remedial plan, for each monthly period since the beginning of 2016.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","52893"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637211","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-18","<p>There are no funding formula implications for Scotland due to changes in the estimated cost of the modernisation of the Great Western railway network in England and Wales. Additional government funding has not been made available. The Barnett formula is only applicable to changes in the departmental expenditure limits of UK Government Departments.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-18T15:00:26.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637211/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637211/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-15","Railways: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the funding formula implications for Scotland are of the £2.1 billion increase in the estimated cost of the modernisation of the Great Western railway network in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","52895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637212","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>Improving air quality is a government wide issue. In addition to engaging at local, national, European and international level to improve air quality, we are also taking action to ensure that Government leads by example on this issue, for instance by supporting reductions in NO<sub>2</sub> and other pollutants through the Government’s operations and purchasing power.</p><p> </p><p>In line with the National Air Quality Plan for nitrogen dioxide published in December 2015, we are currently updating the Government Buying Standards (GBS) for Transport to ensure that NOx emissions are taken into account in procurement decisions. Taking a technology neutral approach focussing on the emissions outcome, the revised GBS will reward manufacturers who reduce the carbon and NOx emissions of their vehicles. This will send a clear message to the market that it is not only carbon emissions that need to be reduced but also vehicle pollutant emissions.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-18T11:35:28.103Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637212/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637212/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Motor Vehicles: Alternative Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking with the Cabinet Office to ensure that public sector fleet operators utilise alternative fuels such as LPG in order to achieve local air quality targets.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","52896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637213","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-23","<p>A redacted summary of the risk assessments report has been placed in the Library.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-23T15:07:41.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637213/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637213/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Unmanned Air Vehicles: Risk Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 15 June 2016 to Question 40015, if he will now place in the Library a redacted summary of the risk assessments commissioned by the Cross-Government Working Group on remotely piloted aircraft system on the use of drones for criminal purposes.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","52972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637214","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-18","<p>These rules are still at the proposal stage, and their primary purpose was to obtain feedback from European citizens. The Government is committed to the development of simple and proportionate regulations for unmanned aircraft and the Civil Aviation Authority will work with the European Aviation Safety Agency over the coming months, as part of an ‘expert rulemaking group’ in which the model flying associations are also represented, in order to achieve this.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-18T10:55:02.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637214/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637214/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Model Aircraft: EU law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 14 November 2016 to Question 52128, if the Government will reject any new proposals for further regulation of new Implementing Rules (Prototype) Regulations which are not proportionate to the risk and undermine the activities of modal aircraft clubs.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","52953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637215","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-21","<p>Government believes we currently have a robust framework that balances penalties with commercial permissions. However, we recognise that this framework needs to keep pace with the emerging market. We continue to develop proposals which we will put forward in the near future.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-21T14:50:13.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637215/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637215/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 27 May 2016 to Question 38311, what the outcome was of the Government's consultation on measures to regulate the use of drones.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","52973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637216","Department for Transport","false","2016-11-21","<p>The A12 from the M25 (Junction 11) to Chelmsford (Junction 15) widening scheme - M25 to Margaretting - is to be developed by Highways England for the next Road Period (2020 - 2025). Construction of the A12 Chelmsford (Junction 19) to the A120 (Junction 25) widening scheme from Boreham Interchange to Colchester is expected to commence before March 2020.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-11-21T13:39:51.84Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637216/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637216/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-15","A12","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for work to commence on uprating the A12 to a three lane road from (a) the M25 to Margaretting and (b) Boreham Interchange to Colchester; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Simon Burns","Chelmsford","Sir Simon Burns","53062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637217","Wales Office","false","2016-11-17","<p>The number of days lost in the Wales Office recorded as being due to mental health disorders at the 31 December for each of the last 3 calendar years is shown below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of days lost</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>51</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>199</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-11-17T12:26:34.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637217/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637217/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-11-15","Wales Office: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in his Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637218","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-21","<p>The total number of working days lost in DWP due to mental illness in each of the last three years is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><p>DWP is committed to improving mental ill health. We support employees through access to comprehensive stress risk assessments, Occupational Health services and our Employee Assistance Programme which offers immediate telephone support 24 hours a day, every day. DWP is currently introducing Mental Health First Aid to further add to the support available.</p><p> </p><p>DWP has greatly reduced sickness absence from an average of 11.1 days in March 2007 to 6.13 days currently. The Department has the lowest average working days lost across Government when compared against other Departments of its size and grade structure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Working Days Lost to mental illness</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Working Days Available</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Working Days Lost as a % of Working Days Available</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01 November 2015 to 31 October 2016</p></td><td><p>114,887</p></td><td><p>16,933,234</p></td><td><p>0.68%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01 November 2014 to 31 October 2015</p></td><td><p>103,596</p></td><td><p>16,288,909</p></td><td><p>0.64%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01 November 2013 to 31 October 2014</p></td><td><p>121,513</p></td><td><p>17,558,267</p></td><td><p>0.69%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-21T17:36:26.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637218/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637218/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Department for Work and Pensions: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many working days were lost due to mental illness in his Department in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","53079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637219","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-18","<p>This information is not gathered by the Department of Work and Pensions.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-18T10:34:31.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637219/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637219/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Social Rented Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of how many properties have been released for letting in Peterborough since the introduction of changes in the spare room subsidy regime; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Stewart Jackson","Peterborough","Mr Stewart Jackson","53043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637220","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-18","<p>The case brought by the Rutherford family was heard with six other cases, therefore separate figures for individual cases are not available. The legal costs (to 9 November 2016) of the Supreme Court proceedings for Rutherford and the other joined cases are £206,841.65.</p><p>The total legal costs of the High Court proceedings for Rutherford and the Court of Appeal proceedings for “A” and Rutherford are £91,772.28.</p><p>These figures include VAT where payable (for example on Counsel’s fees) and disbursements but does not include costs attributable to time spent by Government advisory lawyers, as time spent by such advisory lawyers is not recorded in a manner that allows it to be attributable to individual cases.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-18T10:02:46.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637220/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637220/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Social Rented Housing: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost to the public purse has been of Government legal action in respect of the case brought by the Rutherford family on the spare room subsidy.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","53044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637221","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-18","<p>The Secretary of State for Work and Pensions has made no such representations to the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS). Health and Safety Executive (HSE) officials have liaised with BEIS counterparts about how HSE work can assist the new industrial strategy.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-18T14:55:59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637221/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637221/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations he has made to the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on (a) the link between increased productivity and good safety and health management and (b) that link forming part of the Government's new industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","53039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637222","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-23","<p>A reply was sent to the Rt Hon member by the Department’s Work Services Director for Scotland, Denise Horsfall, on behalf of the Secretary of State on 16 November 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-23T17:28:07.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637222/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637222/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to respond to the letter dated 23 September 2016 from the hon. Member for Gordon on toilet facilities in Ebury House, Aberdeen.","false","Biography information for Alex Salmond","Gordon","Alex Salmond","53143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637223","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-18","<p>This information is not centrally recorded and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-18T09:42:00.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637223/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637223/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Department for Work and Pensions: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department has spent on advertising in each of the last six years in (a) The Sun, (b) The Sunday Times, (c) The Mail on Sunday, (d) The Times, (e) The Sun on Sunday, (f) The Huffington Post, (g) Mail Online, (h) Daily Mail, (i) The Guardian and (j) Trinity Mirror.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","53153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637224","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-21","<p>My Noble Friend the Minister for Welfare Reform (Lord Freud) replied to the hon. Member on 18 November 2016.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-11-21T17:16:46.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637224/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637224/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Glasgow Central of 25 October 2016, requesting that the Government's consultation on tax credit payments be extended.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","53133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637225","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-11-23","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-11-23T16:38:15.187Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637225/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637225/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-11-15","Employment Tribunals Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cases before employment tribunals were from claimants with cancer in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","53113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637226","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-21","<p>Personal Independence Payment (PIP) already recognises that for the most severely disabled claimants, the award review process could seem unnecessarily intrusive. The length of a PIP award is based on an individual’s circumstances and can vary from nine months to an on-going award with a light touch review at the 10 year point. As such, existing PIP claimants with the most severe, lifetime disabilities, whose functional ability has remained the same, are more likely to have their evidence reviewed by a DWP Decision-Maker and will not need to have another face-to-face assessment with a healthcare professional. Regular reviews for PIP claimants are a key feature of the benefit, and ensure that benefit payments accurately match the current needs of claimants.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to engage with stakeholders to improve the service we provide. We are committed to ensuring that the review process works effectively across the spectrum of disabilities and health conditions.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-21T16:53:57.083Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637226/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637226/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Personal Independence Payment: Chronic Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to end the requirement for re-assessments for those with long-term medical conditions who are receiving personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","53014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637227","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-18","<p>The information requested is not collected and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-11-18T14:17:55.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637227/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637227/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Social Security Benefits: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many appointments for claimants transferring from disability living allowance to personal independence payments have been rearranged or cancelled at the request of a person other than the claimant in (a) Plymouth and (b) the South West in the last 12 months; and of those rearranged appointments how many claimants received (i) one strike and (ii) two strikes as a result.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","52915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637228","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-11-23","<p>No estimate has been made as this information is not available.</p><p> </p><p>Information on Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance sanction decisions, by referral reason, is available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/jobseekers-allowance-sanctions" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/jobseekers-allowance-sanctions</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-11-23T15:45:52.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637228/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637228/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-15","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of social security claimants who were sanctioned for late arrival to advisory meetings in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","52913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637229","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-21","<p>The Department does not report specifically on spending against this objective. However, Government recognises the link between living in a cold home and ill-health, and has subsequently invested heavily in improving the energy efficiency of households vulnerable to the effects of the cold, as well as financial payments to help with the affordability of energy bills. Some of these schemes target a range of households, and are not limited to those particularly vulnerable to the effects of cold homes. My noble Friend the Minister of State for Energy and Intellectual Property has asked for the relevant expenditure to be separated out; she will write to the hon. Member with that information and a copy of the letter will be placed in the Libraries of the House.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-21T12:58:59.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637229/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637229/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637229/answer/previousversion/21302","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-15","Death: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department has spent to limit excess winter deaths in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","52942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637230","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-18","<p>Updated prequalification results for the 2016 four-year ahead Capacity Market auction have been published on the Electricity Market Reform Delivery Body’s website<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>. Nearly twenty per cent of the pre-qualified capacity is new-build, and around two thirds of this is from combined cycle gas turbines (CCGTs). Up to 1GW of diesel engines (existing and new) have also prequalified. The competitive nature of the auction means it is difficult to predict the specific technologies and projects that will win agreements.</p><p>On 16<sup>th</sup> November 2016, the Department for Environment Food and Rural Affairs published a consultation on reducing emissions from Medium Combustion Plant and Generators to improve air quality<sup><sup>[2]</sup></sup> – the proposed limits on emissions of nitrogen oxides will apply from 1 January 2019 to any new build generator in scope of the legislation and winning an agreement in this year’s Capacity Market auction.</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.emrdeliverybody.com/CM/prequalification.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.emrdeliverybody.com/CM/prequalification.aspx</a></p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/improving-air-quality-reducing-emissions-from-medium-combustion-plants-and-generators" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/improving-air-quality-reducing-emissions-from-medium-combustion-plants-and-generators</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","52900","2016-11-18T14:01:25.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637230/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637230/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-15","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the likely proportion of capacity that diesel generation could make up in the Capacity Market T-4 auction in winter 2016-17; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","52899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637231","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-18","<p>Updated prequalification results for the 2016 four-year ahead Capacity Market auction have been published on the Electricity Market Reform Delivery Body’s website<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>. Nearly twenty per cent of the pre-qualified capacity is new-build, and around two thirds of this is from combined cycle gas turbines (CCGTs). Up to 1GW of diesel engines (existing and new) have also prequalified. The competitive nature of the auction means it is difficult to predict the specific technologies and projects that will win agreements.</p><p>On 16<sup>th</sup> November 2016, the Department for Environment Food and Rural Affairs published a consultation on reducing emissions from Medium Combustion Plant and Generators to improve air quality<sup><sup>[2]</sup></sup> – the proposed limits on emissions of nitrogen oxides will apply from 1 January 2019 to any new build generator in scope of the legislation and winning an agreement in this year’s Capacity Market auction.</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.emrdeliverybody.com/CM/prequalification.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.emrdeliverybody.com/CM/prequalification.aspx</a></p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/improving-air-quality-reducing-emissions-from-medium-combustion-plants-and-generators" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/improving-air-quality-reducing-emissions-from-medium-combustion-plants-and-generators</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","52899","2016-11-18T14:01:25.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637231/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637231/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-15","Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the likely amount of investment in new large-scale gas power stations that will be delivered through the Capacity Market T-4 auction in winter 2016-17; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","52900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637232","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-21","<p>Integrating graduate skills into the local economy is key to expanding a region’s high skills economy.</p><p> </p><p>Graduates are relatively well represented in the North West compared to most other English regions. The most recent data (2014/15) indicates that approximately 10% (20,500) of first class degree graduates in the UK were employed within the region in the first six months after leaving university. Nearly 75% (14,200) of those employed studied at a Higher Education provider within the region.</p><p>Addressing the skills gap is key to Government’s plans to building a powerhouse in the North and an economy that works for all. We will continue to work with stakeholders to make the North a great place to live and work.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-11-21T10:54:13.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637232/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637232/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-15","Graduates: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to (a) encourage graduates from North West universities to remain in the North West after graduation and (b) attract graduates from across the country to the North West.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","53015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637233","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-23","<p>The Department does not hold this information. Employer’s Liability insurance is a policy matter for the Department for Work and Pensions.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-11-23T15:53:26.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637233/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637233/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-15","Employers' Liability: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support businesses which are threatened with legal action from previous employees affected by asbestosis but which cannot trace any relevant Employer's Liability insurance policy.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","52974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637234","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-18","<p>Ofgem monitors and publishes information on prepayment meters customer accounts in Great Britain; it does not monitor the gas and electricity supply market in Northern Ireland, as this is a devolved matter.</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows either the number or proportion of domestic customers paying by prepayment meters in Great Britain in 2011 to 2015.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2011</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2012</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>No. of PPMs customers</p></td><td><p>Proportion of PPMs customers</p></td><td><p>No. of PPMs customers</p></td><td><p>Proportion of PPMs customers</p></td><td><p>No. of PPMs customers</p></td><td><p>Proportion of PPMs customers</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gas</p></td><td><p>2,912,662</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>3,099,245</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>3,282,080</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Electricity</p></td><td><p>4,094,890</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>4,256,065</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>4,422,504</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2014</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>No. of PPMs customers</p></td><td><p>Proportion of PPMs customers</p></td><td><p>No. of PPMs customers</p></td><td><p>Proportion of PPMs customers</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gas</p></td><td><p>3,399,158</p></td><td><p>15%</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>15.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Electricity</p></td><td><p>4,496,181</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>16.6%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-11-18T16:28:59.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637234/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/637234/answer",,,,,