"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636181","Department of Health","false","2016-11-22","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The autism strategy Think Autism published in 2014 and statutory guidance published in 2015 for local authorities and National Health Service organisations encourages the effective development of local autism strategies for meeting the needs of adults with autism in their local population, as identified in their local needs assessments. Local authorities and clinical commissioning groups should work together to commission services for children with special educational needs, including autism. This should include publishing a ‘Local Offer’ of services.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-11-22T09:49:42.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636181/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636181/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-14","Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many local authorities have published an autism strategy; and what steps the Government is taking to ensure that all local authorities are producing such strategies.","false","Biography information for Oliver Colvile","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Oliver Colvile","52749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636182","Department for Education","false","2016-11-22","<p>The Government committed, following the 2015 Spending Review, to invest £1 billion of additional funding per year in the early years free entitlements, including £300 million per year to increase national average funding rates. The hourly funding rate for each local authority to deliver 30 hours of childcare will be decided by the final early years national funding formula. The hourly funding rate for individual childcare providers will then be set annually by each local authority, following consultation with providers in their area.</p><p> </p><p>The department is developing plans to monitor the implementation of 30 hours of childcare once it is in ‘steady state’ following the full rollout of the scheme from September 2017. We have been clear that getting the funding right is critical to successful delivery of this new entitlement.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-11-22T16:26:08.72Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636182/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636182/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-14","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how often she plans to review the per hour funding allocated to providers as part of the 30 hours free childcare entitlement.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","52741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636183","Department for Education","false","2016-11-22","<p>8 local authorities started delivering the 30 hours childcare entitlement in September 2016, providing invaluable learning ahead of full rollout in September 2017. Over 3,600 children have already accessed an extended entitlement place and we expect this to rise to around 5,000 children over the course of the pilot.</p><p>The Department has since commissioned an independent evaluation of early implementation of the extended entitlement. This evaluation will focus on generating learning that can be used by Early Implementers and all local authorities ahead of national rollout.</p><p>Learning from the early implementers will be shared throughout the year. There will be a national findings event in the spring next year, and a formal evaluation report will be published next summer.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","52743","2016-11-22T16:04:24.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636183/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636183/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-14","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children are receiving 30 hours of free childcare under the pilot of that policy.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","52742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636184","Department for Education","false","2016-11-22","<p>8 local authorities started delivering the 30 hours childcare entitlement in September 2016, providing invaluable learning ahead of full rollout in September 2017. Over 3,600 children have already accessed an extended entitlement place and we expect this to rise to around 5,000 children over the course of the pilot.</p><p>The Department has since commissioned an independent evaluation of early implementation of the extended entitlement. This evaluation will focus on generating learning that can be used by Early Implementers and all local authorities ahead of national rollout.</p><p>Learning from the early implementers will be shared throughout the year. There will be a national findings event in the spring next year, and a formal evaluation report will be published next summer.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","52742","2016-11-22T16:04:24.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636184/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/636184/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-14","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment her Department has made of the pilot of the 30 hours free childcare entitlement.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","52743"
